description: From Latin illaqueatus, past participle of illaqueare; prefix il- (“in”) + laqueare (“to insnare”), from laqueus (“noose, snare”).

verbs.description: illaqueate (third-person singular simple present illaqueates, present participle illaqueating, simple past and past participle illaqueated)

entries.meaning: To ensnare or entrap; to entangle; to catch.
examples: Let not the surpassing eloquence of Taylor dazzle you, nor his scholastic retiary versatility of logic illaqueate your good sense.
